ther_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"created_at":"2022-11-07T22:19:33Z","updated_at":"2022-11-07T22:19:33Z","author_association":"COLLABORATOR","body":"> The training sets of the splits can be composed of ALL the data prior to the cutoff instead of a fixed amount. (The same idea behind ExpandingWindowSplitter).\r\n\r\nAh, I was under the impression that the `CutoffSplitter` uses all data, but it does not. Either way, if it is used in `update` mode, the effect will be the same as in feature 1.\r\n\r\nDesign-wise, I would agree with your suggestions:\r\n* `window_length=None` (not -1 which would be strange) should return all the data prior to the cutoff.\r\n* `fh` as a list makes sense, but unfortunately this would imply an ambiguity. Currently, `int` is allowed, so it is ambiguous what list of int should be. So, allow list of any objects as current, unless it creates an ambiguity (so exclude list of int).\r\n\r\nWould appreciate a PR!\r\n\r\nAny additional thoughts, @khrapovs, as you have looked at the splitters last?\r\n","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sktime/sktime/issues/comments/1306304916/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"performed_via_github_app":null,"event":"commented","actor":{"login":"fkiraly","id":7985502,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjc5ODU1MDI=","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/7985502?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly","html_url":"https:/